<h2 id="honors--awards">Honors &amp; Awards</h2>
<p>“Information Technology and Political Engagement: Mixed Evidence
from Uganda,” has won APSA’s Information Technology &amp; Politics section
award given to the best article published in the previous calendar year. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2021</code></p>

<p>“It Takes a Village: Peer Effects and Externalities in Technology Adoption,” is the recipient of APSA’s Political Networks Section’s Best Conference
Paper Award. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2020</code></p>

<p>“Information, Accountability, and Cumulative Learning,” has won the
Best Book Award in Experimental Research by the Experimental Research
Section of APSA (<a href="https://connect.apsanet.org/s42/best-book-published-in-2019-2/">link</a>) <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2019</code></p>

<p>Comparative Political Studies extraordinary reviewer award. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2019</code></p>

<p>“Information Dissemination, Competitive Pressure, and Politician Performance Between Elections” has won APSA’s Experimental Political Science
Research Best Paper Award (<a href="https://connect.apsanet.org/s42/awards/">link</a>). <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2018</code></p>

<p>“The Political Legacies Of Combat: Attitudes Towards War And Peace
Among Israeli Ex-Combatants,” has won NEPS’s Medal for Best Publication
in Peace Science (<a href="http://www.europeanpeacescientists.org/medal.html">link</a>) <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2016</code></p>

<p>“Do Selection Rules Affect Leader Responsiveness?” has won the
Lawrence Longley Award for the best article on Representation and Electoral
Systems published in 2015 (<a href="http://www.europeanpeacescientists.org/medal.html">link</a>). <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2016</code></p>

